{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nReview-result sidecars (plan- and code-review `REVIEW_RESULT` events) are pruned to the most\nrecent `RETAIN_PER_TICKET = 10` per ticket. Drift-refresh re-reviews on a single ticket can\nexceed 10 rounds, so an auditor loses the earlier rounds. Raise the retention bound to 50 — well\nabove the observed single-digit remediation-loop depth — while still capping unbounded growth of\n`REVIEW_RESULT` events on the `tickets` branch (the hot path of every write). It is a deliberate\nbound, not unlimited retention.\n\n## Current state (the plan review's correction)\n\n`src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py` HAS a `prune()` function and a `RETAIN_PER_TICKET = 10`\nconstant, and its `emit()` calls `prune()`. **`src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py` has NEITHER\na `prune()` function NOR a `RETAIN_PER_TICKET` constant, and its `emit()` does not prune** —\ncode-review `REVIEW_RESULT` events currently grow unbounded (verified: `code_review/sidecar.py`'s\n`emit()` calls only `append_event`, with no prune). So this story does two things: it RAISES the\nplan-review bound to 50, AND it ADDS an equivalent prune path to code-review governed by the SAME\nshared constant, so both paths retain identically.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `src/rebar/llm/plan_review/sidecar.py` — raise `RETAIN_PER_TICKET` from `10` to `50`. Keep the\n  prune newest-first (ordering unchanged); only the retained count changes. This stays the SINGLE\n  definition site of the constant.\n- `src/rebar/llm/code_review/sidecar.py` — ADD retention governed by the SAME constant:\n  - reference the shared bound by IMPORTING it (`from rebar.llm.plan_review.sidecar import\n    RETAIN_PER_TICKET`), so there is ONE named constant object governing both paths — no second\n    literal to drift (import identity, not a copied `50`);\n  - add a `prune(ticket_id, *, keep=RETAIN_PER_TICKET, repo_root=None)` function mirroring\n    `plan_review.sidecar.prune` (list the ticket's `-REVIEW_RESULT.json` events by filename\n    timestamp, `git rm` all but the newest `keep`, commit with `--no-verify`; best-effort and\n    exception-swallowing — a failed prune never fails the gate; filter on this module's own\n    `EVENT_TYPE`);\n  - call `prune(target_ticket, repo_root=repo_root)` from `emit()` after `append_event`, matching\n    plan-review's emit → prune sequence.\n\n## Approach rationale\n\nA single shared constant (imported, not duplicated) keeps the change minimal and makes \"governs\nboth paths\" literally true — one object, one definition site, no second literal to drift (YAGNI: no\nconsumer has asked for a per-repo override; a config key can be added later if a real need appears).\nThe code-review prune reuses the exact newest-first-by-filename-timestamp strategy plan-review\nalready uses, so both paths behave identically.\n\n## Compatibility & rollback\n\nPurely a bound increase plus a new (previously absent) code-review prune. No schema/format change.\nAlready-pruned plan-review history is not recovered (already deleted); going forward more is\nretained. Code-review sidecars that already grew unbounded will be pruned to 50 on the next emit.\nReverting sets the constant back to 10 (prunes more aggressively) and/or removes the code-review\nprune (code-review growth becomes unbounded again); no migration.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] After 50+ reviews on one ticket, up to 50 `REVIEW_RESULT` sidecars are retained and a write\n      past 50 prunes the oldest — for BOTH the plan-review and the code-review sidecar. Oracle: a\n      unit test appending N>50 synthetic events on each path and asserting the retained count is 50\n      and the newest are kept.\n- [ ] The cap is ONE named constant, defined ONCE, governing both prune paths — code-review imports\n      the plan-review constant rather than defining a second literal, AND both prune functions\n      actually honor that one constant. Oracle: a test that (a) asserts\n      `code_review.sidecar.RETAIN_PER_TICKET is plan_review.sidecar.RETAIN_PER_TICKET` (OBJECT\n      IDENTITY, so a copied literal that merely equals 50 fails), (b) asserts there is exactly ONE\n      `RETAIN_PER_TICKET =` assignment in `src/rebar/` (a source scan finding a single definition\n      site — code-review must import, not re-assign), (c) asserts both `prune` functions' `keep`\n      default parameter is that same object, and (d) monkeypatches the single constant to a small N\n      and asserts BOTH prune paths then retain N (proving both paths read the one constant at prune\n      time, not a captured copy).\n- [ ] `code_review.sidecar.emit` prunes after appending — the previously-absent path now exists, so\n      code-review sidecars are bounded at all (they were unbounded before). Oracle: a test that\n      emitting past the cap on a code-review target ticket leaves exactly 50 events.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784075636539110001,"uuid":"8c05ce90-2378-42ac-882f-35f2a4e697de"}